off new ideas for the iPad, gaming, Hollywood content, and more in our Startup Battlefield. After three intense days, one startup will win and take home $50,000 to continue building their vision.</p>\n<p>Disrupt is for innovators in new Internet-enabled  industries: social Web. Mobile computing. Real-time data. Sentiment  analysis. Web targeting. Smart devices. The app ecosystem. The rise of  micro-celebrity. Gaming and virtual goods. And more. Disrupt will  immerse you in debate about what’s changing, why, and how to survive and  thrive in real time. You can’t afford to miss it.&nbsp; So <a href=\"http://disrupt.techcrunch.com/speakers/\">check out who’s coming </a>–then secure your spot at our early-bird rate.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://techcrunchdisrupt2010nyc.eventbrite.com/\"><img title=\"disrupt_tix\" src=\"http://disrupt.techcrunch.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/disrupt_tix.png\" height=\"40\" alt=\"\" width=\"179\" /></a></p><p></p>\n<p>On one day you might hear Lady Gaga’s worldwide manager and digital strategist, Troy  Carter, discuss new realities in content creation and distribution, then  watch CEOs developing fresh musical services face off in the afternoon  in our Startup Battlefield. Or see Twitter backer Fred Wilson debate the  best way to grow a startup, then witness a serial entrepreneur take on a  teen after lunch. Google’s sales head Nikesh Arora will discuss changes  in online advertising and Facebook’s Chris Cox will delve into mobile  strategy, while companies trying to become “the next Google”&nbsp; or “the  next Facebook” compete later in the day. (See our <a href=\"http://disrupt.techcrunch.com#\">Speaker page </a>for  more.)</p>\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid gray; padding: 10px;\">\n<img title=\"startup411\" src=\"http://disrupt.techcrunch.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/startup411.png\" height=\"33\" alt=\"\" width=\"153\" /><br />\nStartup 411 is a special exhibition section devoted to products and services for startups. It features comp